'''Noso Hachimangu''' (曩祖八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Iizuka City|ja|飯塚市|qq=draft}}, Fukuoka Prefecture, Japan. It is a former {{ill|Prefectural shrine|ja|県社|qq=draft}} and currently listed as a {{ill|Betsu Hyōsha|ja|別表神社|qq=draft}} under the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|ja|神社本庁|qq=draft}}. The shrine was previously known as "Noso-no-Miya" (納祖宮).

The shrine is revered as the guardian deity of Iizuka and is also worshipped as a protector of children.

== Deities Enshrined ==
The shrine venerates the following deities:
* {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Emperor Chūai|ja|仲哀天皇|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武内宿禰|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Heavenly and Earthly Deities|ja|天神地祇|qq=draft}}

== History ==
According to legend, {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft}} established an altar in the "Noso Forest" on her return from the {{ill|Sankan Seibatsu|ja|三韓征伐|qq=draft}} campaign to offer prayers to the Heavenly and Earthly Deities and to bid farewell to her loyal retainers from Kyushu. The name "Iizuka" is said to originate from this occasion, as the people proclaimed, "We hope to see your face again someday," with "itsuka" (いつか, someday) evolving into "Iizuka."

The shrine’s records suggest its foundation occurred soon after this event, though the exact date is unknown. By the {{ill|Enbun|ja|延文|qq=draft}} period (1359), shrine buildings had been constructed. It was designated as a Prefectural Shrine in {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft}} 13 (1924).

== festivals and Rituals ==
* **Monthly festival** (Tsukinamisai): 1st day of every month
* **Setsubun Star festival**: February 3
* **Doll Gratitude festival**: 2nd Sunday in May
* **Nagoshinoharae (Chinowa Ritual)**: June 30

